John Edward: Linguistic skills are essential for the citizens of the world
The independent education centres in Scotland have a course of academic excellence that has continued in 2018 with another set of extraordinary results in the examinations that are reinforced by individual and collective successes in the fields of sport, art, music and other community projects.
With more than 30,000 students throughout Scotland, these centres, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Colleges (SCIS) are trying to deliver the best level of service to students and parents.
Independent colleges aim to prepare their students to continue their higher education studies, the career they choose and the place they occupy as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement an adapted study plan, it is observed that modern languages remain a popular and desired assignment in the centres.
As Nelson Mandela said: "If you speak to a man in a language he understands, the message reaches his head.
If you speak in your language, it will reach your heart."
This is a powerful reminder that if you want to establish relationships and build trust with people from other countries, you cannot rely only on English.
If we take into account the recent results of this year's reviews, we can observe that languages are at the highest level in the classification tables, being the highest approval rates in independent colleges.
In total, 68% of students who studied foreign languages obtained an A, the highest score.
The data collected from 74 SCIS centres showed that 72% of students obtained an A in Mandarin, while 72% of German students, 69% of French students and 63% of Spanish students also achieved an A.
This shows that the independent colleges in Scotland support foreign languages because they consider them to be a fundamental competition that both children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
At present, it is considered that, as an assignment, languages are at the same level as CTIM allocations (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the study plans of independent colleges and everywhere.
A 2014 survey by the UK Employment and Skills Commission revealed that, for reasons given by entrepreneurs about the difficulties encountered in covering jobs, 17 % were attributed to the lack of linguistic skills.
Language skills are therefore increasingly necessary to prepare young people for their future careers.
The potential labour opportunities that require languages are increasing, so these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the race that someone chooses, if he has learned a second language, he will have a real advantage in the future thanks to a competition like this, which will last forever.
The fact of being able to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will allow that person to move automatically to competition.
According to a survey conducted by YouTube among over 4,000 adults in the United Kingdom in 2013, 75% of them did not speak any foreign language as well as to maintain a conversation. It was also established that the only language spoken by a percentage of two digits, 15%, was French.
For this reason, investing in language teaching is now important for children today.
If they know a number of languages, especially those of developing economies, children will be equipped to have better opportunities to find quality employment.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Some centres will focus on the most classic modern languages, while others will teach the languages considered most important for the United Kingdom by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of the interests of a child, independent colleges can always choose from a number of languages provided by specialized teaching staff in this area.
The independent education centres in Scotland devote all their efforts to providing a learning environment that prepares children and that equips them with the skills necessary to succeed, whatever the future holds.
At present, it is undisputed that, in a global business environment, languages continue to have a vital importance for the country's future, so this should be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should be considered "competences for international communication".
Independent colleges will continue to offer these options, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
It's a good thing to do.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Colleges
