On Saturday, the Minister of Foreign Affairs of North Korea informed the United Nations that the continuation of sanctions had deepened his mistrust in the United States and that there was no possibility that his country would give up nuclear weapons unilaterally under those circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho stated to the annual General Assembly of the international organization that North Korea had adopted " important measures of good will" over the past year, such as stopping nuclear and missile testing, dismantling nuclear testing facilities and committing itself to the non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"However, we do not receive any similar response from the United States," he said.
"If we do not trust the United States, we cannot trust our national security, and, under these circumstances, there is no possibility that we will disarmament first unilaterally."
Although Ri reiterated the well-known North Korea complaints about Washington's resistance to a phase-by-phase denuclearization formula that rewards the country as it takes steps, its statement is important, as it has not rejected any further unilateral denuclearization, as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong One and Donald Trump after the first summit between an active US president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on 12 June, when Kim committed himself to working for the "denuclearization of the Korean peninsula" and Trump ensured North Korea's security.
North Korea has pursued the official end of the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must give up its nuclear weapons first.
Washington has also resisted appeals to mitigate international sanctions in North Korea.
"The United States has insisted on denuclearization in the first place and has increased the pressure through sanctions in order to achieve its purpose in a coercive manner, including objecting to a declaration of end of war," said Ri.
"The idea that sanctions can make us fall on our knees is a chimera of people who don't know us.
The problem is that the continuation of sanctions deepens our distrust."
Ri made no mention of the plans of a second summit between Kim and Trump, announced by the United Nations leader in early weeks.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings between Kim and Moon Jae, South Korea's leader in the past five months, and added: "If South Korea had been the interested party in denuclearization instead of the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have been in a similar stagnation."
Even so, Ri's tone of speech was radically different from last year's speech, when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable to lead North Korea missiles to US soil after the "malign president" Trump, on a suicide mission, was called Kim "cohet man".
