Federal prosecutors exceptionally seek the death penalty for suspected terrorist attack in New York
The federal prosecutors in New York are looking for the capital penalty for Sayfullo Saipov, the suspect of the terrorist attack in New York City that killed eight people, an exceptional punishment that has not been executed in the state for a federal crime since 1953.
Saipov, 30 years old, allegedly used a Home Depot rental truck to carry out an attack last October on a bicycle car on the West Side motorway of Bajo Manhattan, heading down to the pedestrians and cyclists on his way.
In order to justify a death penalty, prosecutors must prove that Saipov "intendedly" killed the eight victims and "intendedly" caused serious bodily injuries, according to the notice of intention to apply for a death penalty, presented in the South District of New York.
The two charges entail a possible death penalty, according to the court document.
Several weeks after the attack, a large federal jury filed a charge against Saipov with 22 charges including eight charges of murder with organized crime, which are usually used by federal prosecutors in these cases, and a charge of violence and destruction of motorized vehicles.
The attack required "substantial planning and premeditation", according to the prosecutors, who described the way Saipov carried it out as "atrocious, cruel and reckless".
"Sayful Habibullaevic Saipov caused injuries, damage and losses to families and friends of Diego Enrique Angelini, Nicholas Cleves, Ann-Laure Decadt, Darren Drake, Ariel Erlij, Hernan Ferruchi, Hernan Diego Mendoza and Alejandro Damian Pagnucco", is specified in the notice of intent.
Five of the victims were tourists from Argentina.
It has been a decade since the South District of New York processed a death penalty case.
The accused, Khalid Barnes, was found guilty of murdering two drug traffickers, but was finally sentenced to life imprisonment in September 2009.
The last time a death penalty was executed in a federal case in New York went to Julius and Ethel Rosenberg in 1953. This marriage was executed after they were convicted of conspiracy to spy on the Soviet Union during the Cold War two years earlier.
The two Rosenbergs were executed in the electric chair on 19 June 1953.
Saipov, an immigrant from Uzbekistan, demonstrated his lack of remorse during the days and months following the attack, according to judicial documents.
According to the police, he told the investigators that he felt good about what he had done.
According to the charge, Saipov told the authorities that for his attack he was inspired by videos of ISIS on his phone.
He also asked for the ISIS flag to be issued in his hospital room, the police said.
The charge of 22 charges has been declared innocent.
David Patton, one of the federal public defenders lawyers representing Saipov, said they are "of course disappointed" with the prosecutor's decision.
"We believe that the decision to seek the death penalty rather than accept a declaration of guilt with a perpetual sentence of chains without the possibility of release will only prolong the trauma of these events for all the people involved," Patton said.
The Saipov defence team had previously requested prosecutors not to request the death penalty.
